# 🚨 The Error Meaning

> *“No qualifying bean of type RedisTemplate…”*

👉 Spring is telling you:

> “You are injecting `RedisTemplate`, but I don’t know how to create it.”

Even though you added:

```xml
spring-boot-starter-data-redis
```

👉 Spring Boot **does NOT always auto-create a usable `RedisTemplate<Object, Object>`**

---

# ✅ FIX — Add RedisConfig

Create this class in Arthur Core:

```java
package com.yourcompany.arthurcore.config;

import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.datatype.jsr310.JavaTimeModule;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;
import org.springframework.data.redis.connection.RedisConnectionFactory;
import org.springframework.data.redis.core.RedisTemplate;
import org.springframework.data.redis.serializer.*;

@Configuration
public class RedisConfig {

    @Bean
    public RedisTemplate<String, Object> redisTemplate(RedisConnectionFactory connectionFactory) {

        RedisTemplate<String, Object> template = new RedisTemplate<>();
        template.setConnectionFactory(connectionFactory);

        // Key serializer
        template.setKeySerializer(new StringRedisSerializer());
        template.setHashKeySerializer(new StringRedisSerializer());

        // Value serializer (JSON)
        ObjectMapper objectMapper = new ObjectMapper();
        objectMapper.registerModule(new JavaTimeModule());

        GenericJackson2JsonRedisSerializer serializer =
                new GenericJackson2JsonRedisSerializer(objectMapper);

        template.setValueSerializer(serializer);
        template.setHashValueSerializer(serializer);

        template.afterPropertiesSet();
        return template;
    }
}
```

---

# 🧠 Why this is IMPORTANT

Without this:

* Redis stores binary junk ❌
* Serialization breaks ❌
* Dates (Instant) fail ❌
* Debugging becomes painful ❌

With this:

✔ JSON stored in Redis
✔ readable
✔ safe for your `AuthTransaction` and `UserSession`
✔ works with `Instant`

